REACT HOOKS GUIDE

What are React Hooks?
React Hooks allow functional components to use React features such as state, lifecycle methods, refs, and context without class components.

--------------------------------------------------
useState
--------------------------------------------------

Used for managing component state.

Example:

const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

Updating state:

setCount(count + 1);

Using previous value:

setCount(prev => prev + 1);

Best Practices:
- Keep state minimal.
- Group related state together.
- Use functional updates when relying on previous values.

--------------------------------------------------
useEffect
--------------------------------------------------

Used for side effects such as API calls, subscriptions, and timers.

Run once on mount:

useEffect(() => {
  fetchUsers();
}, []);

Run when dependency changes:

useEffect(() => {
  fetchUser(userId);
}, [userId]);

Cleanup:

useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {}, 1000);

  return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, []);

Common Uses:
- API calls
- Event listeners
- Timers
- Local storage synchronization

--------------------------------------------------
useMemo
--------------------------------------------------

Used to memoize expensive calculations.

const total = useMemo(() => {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
}, [items]);

Use Cases:
- Large list filtering
- Complex calculations
- Derived state

--------------------------------------------------
useCallback
--------------------------------------------------

Used to memoize functions.

const handleSubmit = useCallback(() => {
  saveData();
}, []);

Useful when passing functions to child components.

--------------------------------------------------
useRef
--------------------------------------------------

Stores mutable values without causing re-renders.

const inputRef = useRef(null);

inputRef.current.focus();

Use Cases:
- DOM manipulation
- Storing previous values
- Persisting data across renders

--------------------------------------------------
useContext
--------------------------------------------------

Provides access to shared application state.

const user = useContext(UserContext);

Common Uses:
- Authentication
- Theme management
- Global settings

--------------------------------------------------
Custom Hooks
--------------------------------------------------

Example:

function useFetch(url) {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(url)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(setData);
  }, [url]);

  return data;
}

Benefits:
- Code reuse
- Cleaner components
- Easier testing

--------------------------------------------------
React Hook Form
--------------------------------------------------

Basic Setup:

const {
  register,
  handleSubmit,
  control
} = useForm();

Register Input:

<input {...register("name")} />

Controller Example:

<Controller
  name="email"
  control={control}
  render={({ field }) => (
    <TextField {...field} />
  )}
/>

Advantages:
- Better performance
- Less re-rendering
- Easy validation

--------------------------------------------------
Rules of Hooks
--------------------------------------------------

1. Only call hooks at the top level.
2. Never call hooks inside loops.
3. Never call hooks inside conditions.
4. Only call hooks from React functions or custom hooks.

--------------------------------------------------
Common Mistakes
--------------------------------------------------

Incorrect:

if (show) {
  useEffect(() => {});
}

Correct:

useEffect(() => {
  if (show) {
    doSomething();
  }
}, [show]);

--------------------------------------------------
Performance Optimization
--------------------------------------------------

- Use React.memo for expensive child components.
- Use useMemo for expensive calculations.
- Use useCallback for callback functions.
- Avoid unnecessary state updates.
- Avoid deeply nested state objects.